callId can be undefined

If parent renders:
    <CallDetail />
then:
    fetch(`/api/calls/${callId}`)
becomes:
    fetch('/api/calls/undefined')

which may:

hit wrong endpoint
return 404
return unexpected data
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
callId can be null

fetch('/api/calls/null')
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Network failure not handled

If internet/server is down:
fetch(...) //rejects.

Current code has no:
".catch(...)"

Result: Uncaught (in promise) TypeError: Failed to fetch
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Non-200 responses not handled

Suppose server returns:404 Not Found or 500 Internal Server Error
Fetch DOES NOT throw.This still runs:
"r.json()"

Possible issues:
{ error: "Call not found" }
gets stored in state as if it's valid call data.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Response may not be JSON
Suppose backend returns:<html>Server Error</html>
Then:
r.json() throws: SyntaxError: Unexpected token '<'
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Component may render before data exists

State starts as:

const [call, setCall] = useState();

Meaning:

call === undefined

If later JSX does:

<h1>{call.title}</h1>

you get:

Cannot read properties of undefined (reading 'title')

Very common bug.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Race condition when callId changes quickly

Example:

callId = 1
callId = 2
callId = 3

Three requests go out.

If response order becomes:

3 returns first
2 returns second
1 returns last

Then:

setCall(call1)

overwrites newest data.

UI shows wrong call.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
User sees blank screen while fetching.

No:

loading

state exists.

Bad UX.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Missing error state

If API fails:

Failed to fetch

User gets no feedback.

Component silently breaks.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Potential security issue if endpoint requires auth

If API expects:

Authorization: Bearer token

but fetch doesn't send it.

Request may fail with:

401 Unauthorized
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Backend may return unexpected structure

Expected:

{
  "title": "Sales Call",
  "transcript": "..."
}

Actual:

{
  "data": {
    "title": "Sales Call"
  }
}

Then:

call.title

becomes:

undefined
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
callId type mismatch

Suppose route parameter:

callId = {}

Then:

fetch(`/api/calls/${callId}`)

becomes:

/api/calls/[object Object]

Invalid endpoint.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Empty API response

Backend returns:

null

Then:

setCall(null)

Later:

call.title

causes:

Cannot read properties of null
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
JSON parsing can throw

This line:

.then(r => r.json())

can throw if:

malformed JSON
empty body
HTML response
proxy error page

No error handling exists.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Rank	      Problem	                               Impact
1	    Crash on first render (call undefined)	    Critical
2	    No request error handling	                  Critical
3	    HTTP errors not checked	                    High
4	    JSON parse failures	                        High
5	    No loading state	                          High
6	    Race condition on changing callId	          High
7	    No request cancellation	                    Medium-High
8	    Invalid callId handling	                    Medium
9	    Assumes response structure	                Medium
10	  Missing empty state	                        Medium